Adjust rack to top position and preheat #oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @broccoli{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Have, peel, and mince @shallot{1}(peeled and minced).

Toss broccoli on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{}, half the @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, half the @dried thyme{1%teaspoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a #small pot{}, combine @precooked polenta{1} and 1/3 cup @water{} over medium heat. Cook, mashing with a #potato masher{}, until mostly smooth, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Add @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon}, @cream cheese{4%tablespoon}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, half the @Parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon}, 1 TBSP @butter{}, and as much @truffle seasoning{2%g} as you like.

Whisk until cheese melts and polenta is simmering and thickened, ~{2-3%minutes} more. Season with salt and pepper to taste. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Melt 1 TBSP @butter{} in a large, preferably #nonstick pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @Panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}, salt, and pepper; cook, stirring, until golden brown, ~{3-5%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a #small bowl{}. Wipe out pan.

Meanwhile, pat @beef tenderloin filets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season generously all over with remaining garlic powder, remaining thyme, salt, and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in #pan used for panko over medium-high heat. Add beef and cook to desired doneness, ~{4-7%minutes} per side. Turn off heat; transfer beef to a #cutting board{} and tent with #foil{} to keep warm. Wipe out pan.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for beef over medium-high heat. Add minced shallot and cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and tender, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Stir in 1/4 cup water, @beef demi-glace{1}, and any resting juices from beef. Simmer, stirring occasionally, until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Turn off heat. Stir in 1 TBSP @butter{}; taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Once broccoli is done, carefully toss on baking sheet with toasted panko until evenly coated.

Before serving, stir polenta (rewarm over medium heat if necessary).

> If polenta seems too thick, stir in a splash of water.

Divide broccoli, polenta, and beef between plates. Spoon shallot sauce over beef. Sprinkle remaining Parmesan over broccoli and serve.

> Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.